<br>
First, a little of my background so you know where I'm coming from. I am probably older than most of you, maybe younger than some. I have had the distinct pleasure of living and / or working (I am an American) in Japan, Korea, Mexico, Italy, Guam, Greece, and Egypt. This does not make me smarter than those who haven't, it just gives me a wider experience base to work from. I am generally conservative in my politics. My spouse and I make an amount of money that I dreamed about as a youngster; nonetheless it is not considered a GREAT deal of money in today's society (well, at least in today's American society).<br>
<br>
Generally, people who feel very strongly about anything, political or not, are really on the fringe of society. It does not matter whether their views are conservative or liberal.<br>
<br>
Here are a couple of examples:<br>
<br>
&quot;My own experiences have shown that IN GENERAL, the weatheir folk get, the higher in an organizational position, the more lousy, greedy, scummy, back stabbing, moronic, out of touch, un-knowing of the company's actual business etc they get, grrr.<br>
Fact of life is that folk who are powerful, again as a GENERAL RULE, in *any* system, tend to be SCUM BAGS, because scum bags trash anyone and anything to get ahead&quot;..... &quot;Maybe more folk need to see death and destruction before they realize WTF is so important about HUMAN LIFE and happiness.&quot;<br>
<br>
Ok, who are the wealthy people you have been associated with? How are they scum bags? I DO happen to know people that are very well off. They did not get that way by cheating or hurting others. You cannot group ANY segment of the population by a stereotype. That in itself is no better than racism. Have you yourself experienced this death and destruction you tout? More than likely not. Just a guess here, but I bet you are pro-abortion (I am NOT trying to start a debate about the pros and cons of abortion. I am merely citing what I think is an inconsistency of logic dealing with &quot;the importance of human life.&quot;)<br>
<br>
Here is another:<br>
<br>
&quot;i dont understand all you socialism supporters out there .... i would be forced to give most of my income in taxes to the government, allowing only enough to pay my bills .... i dont want to merely exist and pay ungodly amounts of taxes and/or give my money away to others .... i dont see why you support socialism(damn evil communisim) ....&quot;<br>
<br>
After going through these threads, I do not think most of the posters are advocating socialism or communism. In the USSR, citizens were not forced to give back what they had earned, they just earned very little, and most knew only that they were poor. They did not really have access to information that would have allowed them to make a serious comaprison; and no, socialism is definitely not communism.<br>
<br>
What I have learned from personal experience and inferred from watching history unfold around me is this: generally speaking, it does not matter what kind of economic or ideological system you live with, if you want to succeed and prosper within your environment, you can, whether you do that on the backs of others or not. I am not saying that all political or socioeconomic systems are good or even desireable. I merely speak of possibilities. <br>
<br>
Lastly, the people that make the most noise with angry and hostile arguments are probably people that don't really know what they are talking about. They tout data they claim to be facts even though much of it cannot truly be verified. They are most likey uneducated or immature. In many instances, they are probably people that feel wronged or downtrodden in some way and have either chosen someone else to blame or have been told someone else is to blame. Our current world situation is a perfect example of this very thing.<br>
<br>
Have I ruffled some feathers with this commentary? Probably, though that was not truly my intention. Like others have said, I just felt like putting in my two coppers worth.<br>
<br>
